# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bradytroph
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bradytroph/arginine] The one-letter symbol R was assigned to arginine for its phonetic similarity in English.
[src:bradytroph/arginine] Arginine was first isolated in 1886 from yellow lupin seedlings by the German chemist Ernst Schulze and his assistant Ernst Steiger.
[src:bradytroph/arginine] He named it from the Greek *árgyros* (ἄργυρος) meaning "silver" due to the silver-white appearance of arginine nitrate crystals.
[src:bradytroph/arginine] In 1897, Schulze and Ernst Winterstein (1865–1949) determined the structure of arginine.
[src:bradytroph/arginine] Schulze and Winterstein synthesized arginine from ornithine and cyanamide in 1899, but some doubts about arginine's structure lingered until Sørensen's synthesis of 1910.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] An **autotroph** is an organism that can convert abiotic sources of energy into energy stored in organic compounds, which can be used by other organisms.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs produce complex organic compounds (such as carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) using carbon from simple substances such as carbon dioxide, generally using energy from light or inorganic chemical reactions.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs do not need a living source of carbon or energy, and are the producers in a food chain, such as plants on land or algae in water.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs can reduce carbon dioxide to make organic compounds for biosynthesis and as stored chemical fuel.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Most autotrophs use water as the reducing agent, but some can use other hydrogen compounds such as hydrogen sulfide.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs use a portion of the ATP produced during photosynthesis or the oxidation of chemical compounds to reduce NADP+ to NADPH to form organic compounds.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Primary producers are at the lowest trophic level, and are the reasons why Earth sustains life to this day.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Photoautotrophs convert the energy of light into chemical energy through photosynthesis, ultimately building organic molecules from carbon dioxide, an inorganic carbon source.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Chemolithotrophs produce biomass from the oxidation of inorganic chemical compounds; they are frequently found in hydrothermal vents in the deep ocean and include some archaea and bacteria (unicellular organisms).
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Most chemoautotrophs are lithotrophs, using inorganic electron donors such as hydrogen sulfide, hydrogen gas, elemental sulfur, ammonium, and ferrous oxide as reducing agents; and hydrogen sources for biosynthesis and chemical energy release.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Chemolithoautotrophs are microorganisms that synthesize energy through the oxidation of inorganic compounds.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] They can sustain themselves entirely on atmospheric CO2 and inorganic chemicals without the need for light or organic compounds.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] They enzymatically catalyze redox reactions using mineral substrates to generate ATP energy.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] These substrates primarily include hydrogen, iron, nitrogen, and sulfur.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Its ecological niche is often specialized to extreme environments, including deep marine hydrothermal vents, stratified sediment, and acidic hot springs.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Some organisms rely on organic compounds as a source of carbon, but can use light or inorganic compounds as a source of energy.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] An organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds but obtains energy from light is called a *photoheterotroph*, while an organism that obtains carbon from organic compounds and energy from the oxidation of inorganic compounds is termed a *chemolithoheterotroph*.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Evidence suggests that some fungi may also obtain energy from ionizing radiation: Such radiotrophic fungi were found growing inside a reactor of the Chernobyl nuclear power plant.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The term *autotroph* was coined by the German botanist Albert Bernhard Frank in 1892.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] It stems from the ancient Greek word τροφή (*trophḗ*), meaning "nourishment" or "food".
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Without primary producers, organisms that are capable of producing energy on their own, the biological systems of Earth would be unable to sustain themselves.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Plants, along with other primary producers, produce the energy that other living beings consume, and the oxygen that they breathe.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] It is thought that the first organisms on Earth were primary producers located on the ocean floor.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs are fundamental to the food chains of all ecosystems in the world.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] They take energy from the environment in the form of sunlight or inorganic chemicals and use it to create fuel molecules such as carbohydrates.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] This mechanism is called primary production.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Other organisms, called heterotrophs, take in autotrophs as food to carry out functions necessary for their life.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Thus, heterotrophs – all animals, almost all fungi, and most bacteria and protozoa – depend on autotrophs, or primary producers, for the raw materials and fuel they need.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Heterotrophs obtain energy by breaking down carbohydrates or oxidizing organic molecules (carbohydrates, fats, and proteins) obtained in food.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Carnivorous organisms rely on autotrophs indirectly, as the nutrients obtained from their heterotrophic prey come from autotrophs they have consumed.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Most ecosystems are supported by the autotrophic primary production of plants and cyanobacteria that capture photons initially released by the sun.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Plants can only use a fraction (approximately 1%) of this energy for photosynthesis.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The process of photosynthesis splits a water molecule (H2O), releasing oxygen (O2) into the atmosphere, and reducing carbon dioxide (CO2) to release hydrogen atoms that fuel the metabolic process of primary production.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Plants convert and store the energy of the photons into the chemical bonds of simple sugars during photosynthesis.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] These plant sugars are polymerized for storage as long-chain carbohydrates, such as starch and cellulose; glucose is also used to make fats and proteins.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] When autotrophs are eaten by heterotrophs, i.e., consumers such as animals, the carbohydrates, fats, and proteins contained in them become energy sources for the heterotrophs.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Proteins can be made using nitrates, sulfates, and phosphates in the soil.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Aquatic algae are a significant contributor to food webs in tropical rivers and streams.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] This is displayed by net primary production, a fundamental ecological process that reflects the amount of carbon that is synthesized within an ecosystem.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] This carbon ultimately becomes available to consumers.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Net primary production displays that the rates of in-stream primary production in tropical regions are at least an order of magnitude greater than in similar temperate systems.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Researchers believe that the first cellular lifeforms were not heterotrophs as they would rely upon autotrophs since organic substrates delivered from space were either too heterogeneous to support microbial growth or too reduced to be fermented.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Instead, they consider that the first cells were autotrophs.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] These autotrophs might have been thermophilic and anaerobic chemolithoautotrophs that lived at deep sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] This view is supported by phylogenetic evidence – the physiology and habitat of the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) is inferred to have also been a thermophilic anaerobe with a Wood-Ljungdahl pathway, its biochemistry was replete with FeS clusters and radical reaction mechanisms.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The high concentration of K+ present within the cytosol of most life forms suggests that early cellular life had Na+/H+ antiporters or possibly symporters.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Autotrophs possibly evolved into heterotrophs when they were at low H2 partial pressures where the first form of heterotrophy were likely amino acid and clostridial type purine fermentations.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] It has been suggested that photosynthesis emerged in the presence of faint near-infrared light emitted by hydrothermal vents.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The first photochemically active pigments are then thought to be Zn-tetrapyrroles.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The first autotrophic organisms likely evolved early in the Archean but proliferated across Earth's Great Oxidation Event with an increase to the rate of oxygenic photosynthesis by cyanobacteria.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Photoautotrophs evolved from heterotrophic bacteria by developing photosynthesis.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] The earliest photosynthetic bacteria used hydrogen sulfide.
[src:bradytroph/autotroph] Due to the scarcity of hydrogen sulfide, some photosynthetic bacteria evolved to use water in photosynthesis, leading to cyanobacteria.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Prototrophic cells are self-sufficient producers of all required metabolites (e.g. amino acids, lipids, cofactors), while auxotrophs require to be on medium with the metabolite that they cannot produce.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] For example, a methionine auxotrophic cell could only grow on a medium that contained methionine; otherwise, it would starve.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] In this example, this is because it is unable to produce its own methionine.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] However, a methionine prototrophic cell would be able to function and replicate on a medium with or without methionine.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Replica plating is a technique that transfers colonies from one plate to another in the same spot as the last plate so the different media plates can be compared side by side.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] It is used to compare the growth of the same colonies on different plates of media to determine which environments the bacterial colony can or cannot grow in (this gives insight to possible auxotrophic characteristics).
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The method of replica plating implemented by Joshua Lederberg and Esther Lederberg included auxotrophs that were temperature-sensitive; that is, their ability to synthesize was temperature-dependent.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] (Auxotrophs are usually not temperature-dependent.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] They can also depend on other factors.) It is also possible that an organism is auxotrophic to more than just one organic compound that it requires for growth.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] In genetics, a strain is said to be auxotrophic if it carries a mutation that renders it unable to synthesize an essential compound.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] For example, a yeast mutant with an inactivated uracil synthesis pathway gene is a uracil auxotroph (e.g., if the yeast orotidine 5'-phosphate decarboxylase gene is inactivated, the resultant strain is a uracil auxotroph).
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Such a strain is unable to synthesize uracil and will only be able to grow if uracil can be taken up from the environment.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] This is the opposite of a uracil prototroph, or in this case a wild-type strain, which can still grow in the absence of uracil.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Auxotrophic genetic markers are often used in molecular genetics; they were famously used in Beadle and Tatum's Nobel Prize-winning work on the one gene-one enzyme hypothesis, connecting mutations of genes to protein mutations.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] This then allows for biosynthetic or biochemical pathway mapping that can help determine which enzyme or enzymes are mutated and dysfunctional in the auxotrophic strains of bacteria being studied.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Researchers have used strains of *E. coli* auxotrophic for specific amino acids to introduce non-natural amino acid analogues into proteins.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] For instance cells auxotrophic for the amino acid phenylalanine can be grown in media supplemented with an analogue such as para-azido phenylalanine.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Many living things, including humans, are auxotrophic for large classes of compounds required for growth and must obtain these compounds through diet (see vitamin, essential nutrient, essential amino acid, essential fatty acid).
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The complex pattern of evolution of vitamin auxotrophy across the eukaryotic tree of life is intimately connected with the interdependence between organisms.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The Salmonella Mutagenesis test (Ames test) uses multiple strains of *Salmonella typhimurium* that are auxotrophic to histidine to test whether a given chemical can cause mutations by observing its auxotrophic property in response to an added chemical compound.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The mutation a chemical substance or compound causes is measured by applying it to the bacteria on a plate containing histidine then moving the bacteria to a new plate without sufficient histidine for continual growth.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] If the substance does not mutate the genome of the bacteria from auxotrophic to histidine back to prototrophic to histidine, then the bacteria would not show growth on the new plate.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] So by comparing the ratio of the bacteria on the new plate to the old plate and the same ratio for the control group, it is possible to quantify how mutagenic a substance is, or rather, how likely it is to cause mutations in DNA.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] A chemical is considered positive for Ames test if it causes mutations increasing the observed reversion rate and negative if presents similar to the control group.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] There is a normal, but small, number of revertant colonies expected when an auxotrophic bacteria is plated on a media without the metabolite it needs because it could mutate back to prototrophy.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The chances of this are low and therefore cause very small colonies to be formed.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] If a mutagenic substance is added, however, the number of revertants would be visibly higher than without the mutagenic substance.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The Ames test, basically, is considered positive if a substance increases chance of mutation in the DNA of the bacteria enough to cause a quantifiable difference in the revertants of the mutagen plate and the control group plate.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Negative Ames test means the possible mutagen DID not cause increase in revertants and positive Ames test signifies that the possible mutagen DID increase the chance of mutation.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] These mutagenic effects on bacteria are researched as a possible indicator of the same effects on larger organisms, like humans.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] It is suggested that if a mutation can arise in bacterial DNA under presence of a mutagen then the same effect would occur for larger organisms causing cancer.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] A negative Ames test result could suggest that the substance is not a mutagen and would not cause tumor formation in living organisms.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] However only few of the positive Ames Test resulting chemicals were considered insignificant when tested in larger organisms but the positive Ames test for bacteria still could not be conclusively linked to expression of cancer in larger organisms.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] While it can be a possible determinant of tumors for living organisms, humans, animals, and so on, more studies must be completed to come to a conclusion.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] A large number of unnatural amino acids, which are similar to their canonical counterparts in shape, size and chemical properties, are introduced into the recombinant proteins by means of auxotrophic expression hosts.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] For example, methionine (Met) or tryptophan (Trp) auxotrophic *Escherichia coli* strains can be cultivated in a defined minimal medium.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] In this experimental setup it is possible to express recombinant proteins whose canonical Trp and Met residues are completely substituted with different medium-supplemented related analogs.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] This methodology leads to a new form of protein engineering, which is not performed by codon manipulation at the DNA level (e.g. oligonucleotide-directed mutagenesis), but by codon reassignments at the level of protein translation under efficient selective pressure.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] Therefore, the method is referred as selective pressure incorporation (SPI).
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] No organism studied so far encodes other amino acids than the canonical twenty; two additional canonical amino acids (selenocysteine, pyrrolysine) are inserted into proteins by recoding translation termination signals.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] This boundary can be crossed by adaptive laboratory evolution of metabolically stable auxotrophic microbial strains.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] For example, the first clearly successful attempt to evolve *Escherichia coli* that can survive solely on the unnatural amino acid thieno[3,2-b]pyrrolyl) alanine as the only substitute for tryptophan was made in 2015.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] The 1993 film *Jurassic Park* (based on the 1990 Michael Crichton novel of the same name) features dinosaurs that were genetically altered so that they could not produce the amino acid lysine.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] This was known as the "lysine contingency" and was supposed to prevent the cloned dinosaurs from surviving outside the park, forcing them to be dependent on lysine supplements provided by the park's veterinary staff.
[src:bradytroph/auxotroph] In reality, no animals are capable of producing lysine (it is an essential amino acid).
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] As a member of the genus *Bacillus*, *B. subtilis* is rod-shaped and can form a tough, protective endospore, allowing it to tolerate extreme environmental conditions.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It historically has been classified as an obligate aerobe, though evidence exists that it is a facultative anaerobe.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* is considered the best-studied Gram-positive bacterium and a model organism to study bacterial chromosome replication and cell differentiation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It is one of the bacterial champions in secreted enzyme production and used on an industrial scale by biotechnology companies.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] As with other members of the genus *Bacillus*, it can form an endospore to survive extreme environmental conditions of temperature and desiccation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* is a facultative anaerobe and had been considered as an obligate aerobe until 1998.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* is heavily flagellated, which gives it the ability to move quickly in liquids.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Colony, morphological, physiological, and biochemical characteristics of *B. subtilis* are shown in the table below.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] This species is commonly found in the upper layers of the soil and is thought to be a normal gut commensal in humans.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] A 2009 study compared the density of spores found in soil (about 106 spores per gram) to that found in human feces (about 104 spores per gram).
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The number of spores found in the human gut was too high to be attributed solely to consumption through food contamination.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] In some bee habitats, *B. subtilis* appears in the gut flora of honey bees.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* can also be found in marine environments.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Some evidence indicates that *B. subtilis* is saprophytic in nature.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The bacterium exhibits vegetative growth in soil rich in organic matter, and that spores were formed when nutrients were depleted.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Additionally, *B. subtilis* has been shown to form biofilms on plant roots, which might explain why it is commonly found in gut microbiomes.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Perhaps animals eating plants with *B. subtilis* biofilms can foster growth of the bacterium in their gastrointestinal tracts.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The entire lifecycle of *B. subtilis* can be completed in the gastrointestinal tract, which lends credence to the idea that the bacterium enters the gut via plant consumption and stays present as a result of its ability to grow in the gut.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Under stressful conditions, such as nutrient deprivation, *B. subtilis* undergoes the process of sporulation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] This process has been very well studied and has served as a model organism for studying sporulation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Although sporulation in*B. subtilis* is induced by starvation, the sporulation developmental program is not initiated immediately when growth slows due to nutrient limitation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Sporulation is the last-ditch response to starvation and is suppressed until alternative responses prove inadequate.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Even then, certain conditions must be met such as chromosome integrity, the state of chromosomal replication, and the functioning of the Krebs cycle.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Once *B. subtilis* commits to sporulation, the sigma factor sigma F is secreted.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] A sporulation septum is formed and a chromosome is slowly moved into the forespore.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] When a third of one chromosome copy is in the forespore and the remaining two thirds is in the mother cell, the chromosome fragment in the forespore contains the locus for sigma F, which begins to be expressed in the forespore.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] In order to prevent sigma F expression in the mother cell, an anti-sigma factor, which is encoded by spoIIAB, is expressed.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Any residual anti-sigma factor in the forespore (which would otherwise interfere with sporulation) is inhibited by an anti-anti-sigma factor, which is encoded by spoIIAA.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] SpoIIAA is located near the locus for the sigma factor, so it is consistently expressed in the forespore.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Since the spoIIAB locus is not located near the sigma F and spoIIAA loci, it is expressed only in the mother cell and therefore repress sporulation in that cell, allowing sporulation to continue in the forespore.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Residual spoIIAA in the mother cell represses spoIIAB, but spoIIAB is constantly replaced so it continues to inhibit sporulation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] When the full chromosome localizes to the forespore, spoIIAB can repress sigma F.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Sporulation requires a great deal of time and also a lot of energy, making it crucial for a cell to monitor its surroundings efficiently and ensure that sporulation is embarked upon at only the most appropriate times.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The wrong decision can be catastrophic: a vegetative cell will die if the conditions are too harsh, while bacteria forming spores in an environment which is conducive to vegetative growth will be out competed.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] In short, initiation of sporulation is a very tightly regulated network with numerous checkpoints for efficient control.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The complete genome sequence of *B. subtilis* sub-strain QB928 has 4,146,839 DNA base pairs and 4,292 genes.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The QB928 strain is widely used in genetic studies due to the presence of various markers [aroI(aroK)906 purE1 dal(alrA)1 trpC2].
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Several noncoding RNAs have been characterized in the *B. subtilis* genome in 2009, including Bsr RNAs.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Microarray-based comparative genomic analyses have revealed that *B. subtilis* members show considerable genomic diversity.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] FsrA, a small RNA found in *B. subtilis*, is an effector of the iron-sparing response and acts to down-regulate iron-containing proteins in times of poor iron bioavailability.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] A promising fish probiotic, *B. subtilis* strain WS1A, possesses antimicrobial activity against *Aeromonas veronii* and suppressed motile *Aeromonas* septicemia in *Labeo rohita*.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The *de novo* assembly resulted in an estimated chromosome size of 4,148,460 bp, with 4,288 open reading frames.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* strain WS1A genome contains many potential genes, such as those encoding proteins involved in the biosynthesis of riboflavin, vitamin B6, and amino acids (*ilvD*) and in carbon utilization (*pta*).
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Studies using computational metabolic modeling have shown that gene essentiality in *B. subtilis* can vary depending on environmental conditions.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Flux balance analysis simulations indicate that while some genes remain consistently essential for growth, others exhibit condition-dependent essentiality under nutrient or oxygen limitation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Under nutrient-limited conditions, such as glucose or nitrogen restriction, metabolic activity shifts between biomass production and maintenance processes, altering growth outcomes.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] These findings suggest that metabolic robustness in *B. subtilis* involves tradeoffs between rapid growth and long-term survival under environmental stresses.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] In response to nutrient limitation, *B. subtilis* can also initiate adaptive physiological responses, including metabolic diversification and endospore formation under prolonged stress.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Natural bacterial transformation involves the transfer of DNA from one bacterium to another through the surrounding medium.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] In *B. subtilis*, the length of transferred DNA is greater than 1,271kb (more than 1million bases).
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The transferred DNA is likely double-stranded DNA and is often more than a third of the total chromosome length of 4,215kb.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It appears that about 7–9% of the recipient cells take up an entire chromosome.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] For a recipient bacterium to bind, take up exogenous DNA from another bacterium of the same species, and recombine it into its chromosome, it must enter a special physiological state called competence.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Competence in *B. subtilis* is induced toward the end of logarithmic growth, especially under conditions of amino-acid limitation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Under these stressful conditions of semistarvation, cells typically have just one copy of their chromosome and likely have increased DNA damage.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] To test whether transformation is an adaptive function for *B. subtilis* to repair its DNA damage, experiments were conducted using UV light as the damaging agent.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] These experiments led to the conclusion that competence, with uptake of DNA, is specifically induced by DNA-damaging conditions, and that transformation functions as a process for recombinational repair of DNA damage.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] While the natural competent state is common within laboratory *B. subtilis* samples and field isolates, some industrially relevant strains, e.g.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* (natto), are reluctant to take up DNA due to the presence of restriction modification systems that degrade exogenous DNA.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] *B. subtilis* (natto) mutants, which are defective in a type I restriction modification system endonuclease, are able to act as recipients of conjugative plasmids in mating experiments, paving the way for further genetic engineering of this particular strain.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Cultures of *B. subtilis* were popular worldwide, before the introduction of antibiotics, as an immunostimulatory agent to aid treatment of gastrointestinal and urinary tract diseases.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It was marketed throughout America and Europe from 1946 as an immunostimulatory aid in the treatment of gut and urinary tract diseases such as rotavirus and shigellosis.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Army dumped *B. subtilis* onto the grates of New York City subway stations for five days to observe how a biological agent dispensed around the subway trains would disperse and potentially affect unsuspecting passengers.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Due to its ability to survive, it is thought to still be present there.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The antibiotic bacitracin was first isolated from a variety of *Bacillus licheniformis* named "Tracy I" in 1945, then considered part of the *B. subtilis* species.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It is still commercially manufactured by growing the variety in a container of liquid growth medium.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Over time, the bacteria synthesize bacitracin and secrete the antibiotic into the medium.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The bacitracin is then extracted from the medium using chemical processes.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Since the 1960s, *B. subtilis* has had a history as a test species in spaceflight experimentation.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Its endospores can survive up to 6 years in space if coated by dust particles protecting it from solar UV rays.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] It has been used as an extremophile survival indicator in outer space such as Exobiology Radiation Assembly, EXOSTACK, and EXPOSE orbital missions.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Wild-type natural isolates of *B. subtilis* are difficult to work with compared with laboratory strains that have undergone domestication processes of mutagenesis and selection.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] These strains often have improved capabilities of transformation (uptake and integration of environmental DNA), growth, and loss of abilities needed "in the wild".
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] While dozens of different strains fitting this description exist, the strain designated '168' is the most widely used.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] Strain 168, a tryptophan auxotroph isolated after X-ray mutagenesis of *B. subtilis* Marburg strain, is widely used in research due to its high transformation efficiency.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] A strain of *B. subtilis* formerly known as *Bacillus natto* is used in the commercial production of the Japanese food *nattō*, as well as the similar Korean food *cheonggukjang*.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The fermented beans are recognized for their contribution to a healthy gut flora and vitamin K2 intake; during this long history of widespread use, *natto* has not been implicated in adverse events potentially attributable to the presence of *B. subtilis*.
[src:bradytroph/bacillus-subtilis] The *natto* product and the *B. subtilis* *natto* as its principal component are Foods for Specified Health Use approved by the Japanese Ministry of Health, Labour, and Welfare as effective for preservation of health.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] A **bradytroph** is a strain of an organism that exhibits slow growth in the absence of an external source of a particular metabolite.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] This is usually due to a defect in an enzyme required in the metabolic pathway producing this chemical.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] Such defects are the result of mutations in the genes encoding these enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] As the organism can still produce small amounts of the chemical, the mutation is not lethal.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] In these bradytroph strains, rapid growth occurs when the chemical is present in the cell's growth media and the missing metabolite can be transported into the cell from the external environment.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] A bradytroph may also be referred to as a "leaky auxotroph".
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] The first usage of "bradytroph" was to describe *Escherichia coli* mutants partially defective in arginine biosynthesis.
[src:bradytroph/bradytroph] Among many other examples of bradytrophic strains of microorganisms are *Bacillus subtilis* strains with mutations affecting thiamine production and *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* strains with mutations that impair arginine biosynthesis.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] The study of cells is performed using microscopy techniques, cell culture, and cell fractionation.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] These are used for research into how cells function, which ultimately gives insight into larger organisms.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Knowing the components of cells and how cells work is fundamental to all biological sciences and is essential for research in biomedical fields such as cancer, and other diseases.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Research in cell biology is interconnected to other fields such as genetics, molecular genetics, molecular biology, medical microbiology, immunology, and cytochemistry.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Cells were first seen in 17th-century Europe with the invention of the compound microscope.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] In 1665, Robert Hooke referred to the building blocks of all living organisms as "cells" (published in *Micrographia*) after looking at a piece of cork and observing a structure reminiscent of monastic cells; however, the cells were dead.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] They gave no indication to the actual overall components of a cell.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] A few years later, in 1674, Anton Van Leeuwenhoek was the first to analyze live cells in his examination of algae.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Many years later, in 1831, Robert Brown discovered the nucleus.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] All of this preceded the cell theory which states that all living things are made up of cells and that cells are organisms' functional and structural units.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] This was ultimately concluded by plant scientist Matthias Schleiden and animal scientist Theodor Schwann in 1838, who viewed live cells in plant and animal tissue, respectively.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] 19 years later, Rudolf Virchow further contributed to the cell theory, adding that all cells come from the division of pre-existing cells.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Viruses are not considered in cell biology – they lack the characteristics of a living cell and instead are studied in the microbiology subclass of virology.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Cell biology research looks at different ways to culture and manipulate cells outside of a living body to further research in human anatomy and physiology, and to derive medications.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] The techniques by which cells are studied have evolved.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Due to advancements in microscopy, techniques and technology have allowed scientists to hold a better understanding of the structure and function of cells.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] The scientific branch that studies and diagnoses diseases on the cellular level is called cytopathology.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Cytopathology is generally used on samples of free cells or tissue fragments, in contrast to the pathology branch of histopathology, which studies whole tissues.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] Cytopathology is commonly used to investigate diseases involving a wide range of body sites, often to aid in the diagnosis of cancer but also in the diagnosis of some infectious diseases and other inflammatory conditions.
[src:bradytroph/cell-biology] For example, a common application of cytopathology is the Pap smear, a screening test used to detect cervical cancer, and precancerous cervical lesions that may lead to cervical cancer.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An **enzyme** is a biological macromolecule, usually a protein, that acts as a biological catalyst, accelerating chemical reactions without being consumed in the process.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The molecules on which enzymes act are called substrates, which are converted into products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Nearly all metabolic processes within a cell depend on enzyme catalysis to occur at biologically relevant rates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A metabolic pathway is typically composed of a series of enzyme-catalyzed steps.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The study of enzymes is known as *enzymology*, and a related field focuses on pseudoenzymes—proteins that have lost catalytic activity but may retain regulatory or scaffolding functions, often indicated by alterations in their amino acid sequences or unusual 'pseudocatalytic' behavior.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are known to catalyze over 5,000 types of biochemical reactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Other biological catalysts include catalytic RNA molecules, or ribozymes, which are sometimes classified as enzymes despite being composed of RNA rather than protein.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] More recently, biomolecular condensates have been recognized as a third category of biocatalysts, capable of catalyzing reactions by creating interfaces and gradients—such as ionic gradients—that drive biochemical processes, even when their component proteins are not intrinsically catalytic.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes increase the reaction rate by lowering a reaction's activation energy, often by factors of millions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A striking example is orotidine 5′-phosphate decarboxylase, which accelerates a reaction that would otherwise take millions of years to occur in milliseconds.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Like all catalysts, enzymes do not affect the overall equilibrium of a reaction and are regenerated at the end of each cycle.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] What distinguishes them is their high specificity, determined by their unique three-dimensional structure, and their sensitivity to factors such as temperature and pH.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme activity can be enhanced by activators or diminished by inhibitors, many of which serve as drugs or poisons.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Outside optimal conditions, enzymes may lose their structure through denaturation, leading to loss of function.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes have widespread practical applications.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In industry, they are used to catalyze the production of antibiotics and other complex molecules.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In everyday life, enzymes in biological washing powders break down protein, starch, and fat stains, enhancing cleaning performance.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Papain and other proteolytic enzymes are used in meat tenderizers to hydrolyze proteins, improving texture and digestibility.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Their specificity and efficiency make enzymes indispensable in both biological systems and commercial processes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] By the late 17th and early 18th centuries, the digestion of meat by stomach secretions and the conversion of starch to sugars by plant extracts and saliva were known but the mechanisms by which these occurred had not been identified.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] French chemist Anselme Payen was the first to discover an enzyme, diastase, in 1833.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A few decades later, when studying the fermentation of sugar to alcohol by yeast, Louis Pasteur concluded that this fermentation was caused by a vital force contained within the yeast cells called "ferments", which were thought to function only within living organisms.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In 1877, German physiologist Wilhelm Kühne (1837–1900) first used the term *enzyme*, which comes from Ancient Greek ἔνζυμον*(énzymon)* 'leavened, in yeast', to describe this process.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The word *enzyme* was used later to refer to nonliving substances such as pepsin, and the word *ferment* was used to refer to chemical activity produced by living organisms.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Eduard Buchner submitted his first paper on the study of yeast extracts in 1897.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In a series of experiments at the University of Berlin, he found that sugar was fermented by yeast extracts even when there were no living yeast cells in the mixture.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] He named the enzyme that brought about the fermentation of sucrose "zymase".
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In 1907, he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry for "his discovery of cell-free fermentation".
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Following Buchner's example, enzymes are usually named according to the reaction they carry out: the suffix *-ase* is combined with the name of the substrate (e.g., lactase is the enzyme that cleaves lactose) or to the type of reaction (e.g., DNA polymerase forms DNA polymers).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The biochemical identity of enzymes was still unknown in the early 1900s.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Many scientists observed that enzymatic activity was associated with proteins, but others (such as Nobel laureate Richard Willstätter) argued that proteins were merely carriers for the true enzymes and that proteins *per se* were incapable of catalysis.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Sumner showed that the enzyme urease was a pure protein and crystallized it; he did likewise for the enzyme catalase in 1937.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The conclusion that pure proteins can be enzymes was definitively demonstrated by John Howard Northrop and Wendell Meredith Stanley, who worked on the digestive enzymes pepsin (1930), trypsin and chymotrypsin.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These three scientists were awarded the 1946 Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The discovery that enzymes could be crystallized eventually allowed their structures to be solved by x-ray crystallography.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This was first done for lysozyme, an enzyme found in tears, saliva and egg whites that digests the coating of some bacteria; the structure was solved by a group led by David Chilton Phillips and published in 1965.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This high-resolution structure of lysozyme marked the beginning of the field of structural biology and the effort to understand how enzymes work at an atomic level of detail.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can be classified by two main criteria: either their enzymatic activity or their amino acid sequence similarity (and thus evolutionary relationship).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An enzyme's name is often derived from its substrate or the chemical reaction it catalyzes, with the word ending in *-ase*.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Examples are lactase, alcohol dehydrogenase and DNA polymerase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Different enzymes that catalyze the same chemical reaction are called isozymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The International Union of Biochemistry and Molecular Biology have developed a nomenclature for enzymes, the EC numbers (for "Enzyme Commission").
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Each enzyme is described by "EC" followed by a sequence of four numbers which represent the hierarchy of enzymatic activity (from very general to very specific).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] That is, the first number broadly classifies the enzyme based on its mechanism while the other digits add more and more specificity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These sections are subdivided by other features such as the substrate, products, and chemical mechanism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An enzyme is fully specified by four numerical designations.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, hexokinase (EC 2.7.1.1) is a transferase (EC 2) that adds a phosphate group (EC 2.7) to a hexose sugar, a molecule containing an alcohol group (EC 2.7.1).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] EC categories do not reflect sequence similarity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For instance, two ligases of the same EC number that catalyze exactly the same reaction can have completely different sequences.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Independent of their function, enzymes, like any other proteins, have been classified by their sequence similarity into numerous families.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These families have been documented in dozens of different protein and protein family databases such as Pfam.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Unrelated enzymes that have the same enzymatic activity have been called *non-homologous isofunctional enzymes*.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Horizontal gene transfer may spread these genes to unrelated species, especially bacteria where they can replace endogenous genes of the same function, leading to hon-homologous gene displacement.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are generally globular proteins, acting alone or in larger complexes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The sequence of the amino acids specifies the structure which in turn determines the catalytic activity of the enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Although structure determines function, a novel enzymatic activity cannot yet be predicted from structure alone.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme structures unfold (denature) when heated or exposed to chemical denaturants and this disruption to the structure typically causes a loss of activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are usually much larger than their substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Sizes range from just 62 amino acid residues, for the monomer of 4-oxalocrotonate tautomerase, to over 2,500 residues in the animal fatty acid synthase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Only a small portion of their structure (around 2–4 amino acids) is directly involved in catalysis: the catalytic site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This catalytic site is located next to one or more binding sites where residues orient the substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The catalytic site and binding site together compose the enzyme's active site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The remaining majority of the enzyme structure serves to maintain the precise orientation and dynamics of the active site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In some enzymes, no amino acids are directly involved in catalysis; instead, the enzyme contains sites to bind and orient catalytic cofactors.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme structures may also contain allosteric sites where the binding of a small molecule causes a conformational change that increases or decreases activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A small number of RNA-based biological catalysts called ribozymes exist, which again can act alone or in complex with proteins.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The most common of these is the ribosome which is a complex of protein and catalytic RNA components.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes must bind their substrates before they can catalyze any chemical reaction.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are usually very specific as to what substrates they bind and then the chemical reaction catalyzed.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Specificity is achieved by binding pockets with complementary shape, charge and hydrophilic/hydrophobic characteristics to the substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can therefore distinguish between very similar substrate molecules to be chemoselective, regioselective and stereospecific.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Some of the enzymes showing the highest specificity and accuracy are involved in the copying and expression of the genome.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Some of these enzymes have "proof-reading" mechanisms.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Here, an enzyme such as DNA polymerase catalyzes a reaction in a first step and then checks that the product is correct in a second step.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This two-step process results in average error rates of less than 1 error in 100 million reactions in high-fidelity mammalian polymerases.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Similar proofreading mechanisms are also found in RNA polymerase, aminoacyl tRNA synthetases and ribosomes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Conversely, some enzymes display enzyme promiscuity, having broad specificity and acting on a range of different physiologically relevant substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Many enzymes possess small side activities which arose fortuitously (i.e. neutrally), which may be the starting point for the evolutionary selection of a new function.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] To explain the observed specificity of enzymes, in 1894 Emil Fischer proposed that both the enzyme and the substrate possess specific complementary geometric shapes that fit exactly into one another.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This is often referred to as "the lock and key" model.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This early model explains enzyme specificity, but fails to explain the stabilization of the transition state that enzymes achieve.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In 1958, Daniel Koshland suggested a modification to the lock and key model: since enzymes are rather flexible structures, the active site is continuously reshaped by interactions with the substrate as the substrate interacts with the enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] As a result, the substrate does not simply bind to a rigid active site; the amino acid side-chains that make up the active site are molded into the precise positions that enable the enzyme to perform its catalytic function.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In some cases, such as glycosidases, the substrate molecule also changes shape slightly as it enters the active site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The active site continues to change until the substrate is completely bound, at which point the final shape and charge distribution is determined.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Induced fit may enhance the fidelity of molecular recognition in the presence of competition and noise via the conformational proofreading mechanism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes may use several of these mechanisms simultaneously.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, proteases such as trypsin perform covalent catalysis using a catalytic triad, stabilize charge build-up on the transition states using an oxyanion hole, complete hydrolysis using an oriented water substrate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are not rigid, static structures; instead they have complex internal dynamic motions – that is, movements of parts of the enzyme's structure such as individual amino acid residues, groups of residues forming a protein loop or unit of secondary structure, or even an entire protein domain.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These motions give rise to a conformational ensemble of slightly different structures that interconvert with one another at equilibrium.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Different states within this ensemble may be associated with different aspects of an enzyme's function.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, different conformations of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase are associated with the substrate binding, catalysis, cofactor release, and product release steps of the catalytic cycle, consistent with catalytic resonance theory.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The transitions between the different conformations during the catalytic cycle involve internal viscoelastic motion that is facilitated by high-strain regions where amino acids are rearranged.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Substrate presentation is a process where the enzyme is sequestered away from its substrate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can be sequestered to the plasma membrane away from a substrate in the nucleus or cytosol.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Or within the membrane, an enzyme can be sequestered into lipid rafts away from its substrate in the disordered region.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] When the enzyme is released it mixes with its substrate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Alternatively, the enzyme can be sequestered near its substrate to activate the enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the enzyme can be soluble and upon activation bind to a lipid in the plasma membrane and then act upon molecules in the plasma membrane.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Allosteric sites are pockets on the enzyme, distinct from the active site, that bind to molecules in the cellular environment.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These molecules then cause a change in the conformation or dynamics of the enzyme that is transduced to the active site and thus affects the reaction rate of the enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In this way, allosteric interactions can either inhibit or activate enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Allosteric interactions with metabolites upstream or downstream in an enzyme's metabolic pathway cause feedback regulation, altering the activity of the enzyme according to the flux through the rest of the pathway.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Some enzymes do not need additional components to show full activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Others require non-protein molecules called cofactors to be bound for activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Cofactors can be either inorganic (e.g., metal ions and iron–sulfur clusters) or organic compounds (e.g., flavin and heme).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These cofactors serve many purposes; for instance, metal ions can help in stabilizing nucleophilic species within the active site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Organic cofactors can be either coenzymes, which are released from the enzyme's active site during the reaction, or prosthetic groups, which are tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Organic prosthetic groups can be covalently bound (e.g., biotin in enzymes such as pyruvate carboxylase).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An example of an enzyme that contains a cofactor is carbonic anhydrase, which uses a zinc cofactor bound as part of its active site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These tightly bound ions or molecules are usually found in the active site and are involved in catalysis.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, flavin and heme cofactors are often involved in redox reactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes that require a cofactor but do not have one bound are called *apoenzymes* or *apoproteins*.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An enzyme together with the cofactor(s) required for activity is called a *holoenzyme* (or haloenzyme).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The term *holoenzyme* can also be applied to enzymes that contain multiple protein subunits, such as the DNA polymerases; here the holoenzyme is the complete complex containing all the subunits needed for activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Coenzymes are small organic molecules that can be loosely or tightly bound to an enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Coenzymes transport chemical groups from one enzyme to another.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Examples include NADH, NADPH and adenosine triphosphate (ATP).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Some coenzymes, such as flavin mononucleotide (FMN), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), thiamine pyrophosphate (TPP), and tetrahydrofolate (THF), are derived from vitamins.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These coenzymes cannot be synthesized by the body *de novo* and closely related compounds (vitamins) must be acquired from the diet.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Since coenzymes are chemically changed as a consequence of enzyme action, it is useful to consider coenzymes to be a special class of substrates, or second substrates, which are common to many different enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, about 1000 enzymes are known to use the coenzyme NADH.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Coenzymes are usually continuously regenerated and their concentrations maintained at a steady level inside the cell.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, NADPH is regenerated through the pentose phosphate pathway and *S*-adenosylmethionine by methionine adenosyltransferase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This continuous regeneration means that small amounts of coenzymes can be used very intensively.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the human body turns over its own weight in ATP each day.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] As with all catalysts, enzymes do not alter the position of the chemical equilibrium of the reaction.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In the presence of an enzyme, the reaction runs in the same direction as it would without the enzyme, just more quickly.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The rate of a reaction is dependent on the activation energy needed to form the transition state which then decays into products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes increase reaction rates by lowering the energy of the transition state.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] First, binding forms a low energy enzyme-substrate complex (ES).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Second, the enzyme stabilises the transition state such that it requires less energy to achieve compared to the uncatalyzed reaction (ES‡).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Finally the enzyme-product complex (EP) dissociates to release the products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can couple two or more reactions, so that a thermodynamically favorable reaction can be used to "drive" a thermodynamically unfavourable one so that the combined energy of the products is lower than the substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the hydrolysis of ATP is often used to drive other chemical reactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] for an enzyme reaction showing the relation between the substrate concentration and reaction rate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme kinetics is the investigation of how enzymes bind substrates and turn them into products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The rate data used in kinetic analyses are commonly obtained from enzyme assays.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In 1913 Leonor Michaelis and Maud Leonora Menten proposed a quantitative theory of enzyme kinetics, which is referred to as Michaelis–Menten kinetics.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The major contribution of Michaelis and Menten was to think of enzyme reactions in two stages.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In the first, the substrate binds reversibly to the enzyme, forming the enzyme-substrate complex.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This is sometimes called the Michaelis–Menten complex in their honor.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The enzyme then catalyzes the chemical step in the reaction and releases the product.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Haldane, who derived kinetic equations that are still widely used today.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme rates depend on solution conditions and substrate concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] To find the maximum speed of an enzymatic reaction, the substrate concentration is increased until a constant rate of product formation is seen.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This is shown in the saturation curve on the right.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Saturation happens because, as substrate concentration increases, more and more of the free enzyme is converted into the substrate-bound ES complex.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] At the maximum reaction rate (*V*max) of the enzyme, all the enzyme active sites are bound to substrate, and the amount of ES complex is the same as the total amount of enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The efficiency of an enzyme can be expressed in terms of *k*cat/*K*m.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This is also called the specificity constant and incorporates the rate constants for all steps in the reaction up to and including the first irreversible step.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Because the specificity constant reflects both affinity and catalytic ability, it is useful for comparing different enzymes against each other, or the same enzyme with different substrates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The theoretical maximum for the specificity constant is called the diffusion limit and is about 108 to 109 (M−1 s−1).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] At this point every collision of the enzyme with its substrate will result in catalysis, and the rate of product formation is not limited by the reaction rate but by the diffusion rate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes with this property are called *catalytically perfect* or *kinetically perfect*.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Example of such enzymes are triose-phosphate isomerase, carbonic anhydrase, acetylcholinesterase, catalase, fumarase, β-lactamase, and superoxide dismutase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The turnover of such enzymes can reach several million reactions per second.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Michaelis–Menten kinetics relies on the law of mass action, which is derived from the assumptions of free diffusion and thermodynamically driven random collision.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Many biochemical or cellular processes deviate significantly from these conditions, because of macromolecular crowding and constrained molecular movement.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] More recent, complex extensions of the model attempt to correct for these effects.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] (right) are very similar in structure (differences show in green).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] As a result, methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of many enzymes that use folates.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme reaction rates can be decreased by various types of enzyme inhibitors.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A competitive inhibitor and substrate cannot bind to the enzyme at the same time.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Often competitive inhibitors strongly resemble the real substrate of the enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the drug methotrexate is a competitive inhibitor of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase, which catalyzes the reduction of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The similarity between the structures of dihydrofolate and this drug are shown in the accompanying figure.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This type of inhibition can be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In some cases, the inhibitor can bind to a site other than the binding-site of the usual substrate and exert an allosteric effect to change the shape of the usual binding-site.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A non-competitive inhibitor binds to a site other than where the substrate binds.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The substrate still binds with its usual affinity and hence Km remains the same.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] However the inhibitor reduces the catalytic efficiency of the enzyme so that Vmax is reduced.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In contrast to competitive inhibition, non-competitive inhibition cannot be overcome with high substrate concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An uncompetitive inhibitor cannot bind to the free enzyme, only to the enzyme-substrate complex; hence, these types of inhibitors are most effective at high substrate concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In the presence of the inhibitor, the enzyme-substrate complex is inactive.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A mixed inhibitor binds to an allosteric site and the binding of the substrate and the inhibitor affect each other.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The enzyme's function is reduced but not eliminated when bound to the inhibitor.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This type of inhibitor does not follow the Michaelis–Menten equation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An irreversible inhibitor permanently inactivates the enzyme, usually by forming a covalent bond to the protein.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Penicillin and aspirin are common drugs that act in this manner.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In many organisms, inhibitors may act as part of a feedback mechanism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] If an enzyme produces too much of one substance in the organism, that substance may act as an inhibitor for the enzyme at the beginning of the pathway that produces it, causing production of the substance to slow down or stop when there is sufficient amount.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Major metabolic pathways such as the citric acid cycle make use of this mechanism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Since inhibitors modulate the function of enzymes they are often used as drugs.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Many such drugs are reversible competitive inhibitors that resemble the enzyme's native substrate, similar to methotrexate above; other well-known examples include statins used to treat high cholesterol, and protease inhibitors used to treat retroviral infections such as HIV.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A common example of an irreversible inhibitor that is used as a drug is aspirin, which inhibits the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes that produce the inflammation messenger prostaglandin.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the poison cyanide is an irreversible enzyme inhibitor that combines with the copper and iron in the active site of the enzyme cytochrome c oxidase and blocks cellular respiration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] As enzymes are made up of proteins, their actions are sensitive to change in many physio chemical factors such as pH, temperature, substrate concentration, etc.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The following table shows pH optima for various enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes serve a wide variety of functions inside living organisms.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] They are indispensable for signal transduction and cell regulation, often via kinases and phosphatases.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] They also generate movement, with myosin hydrolyzing adenosine triphosphate (ATP) to generate muscle contraction, and also transport cargo around the cell as part of the cytoskeleton.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Other ATPases in the cell membrane are ion pumps involved in active transport.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are also involved in more exotic functions, such as luciferase generating light in fireflies.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Viruses can also contain enzymes for infecting cells, such as the HIV integrase and reverse transcriptase, or for viral release from cells, like the influenza virus neuraminidase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An important function of enzymes is in the digestive systems of animals.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes such as amylases and proteases break down large molecules (starch or proteins, respectively) into smaller ones, so they can be absorbed by the intestines.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Starch molecules, for example, are too large to be absorbed from the intestine, but enzymes hydrolyze the starch chains into smaller molecules such as maltose and eventually glucose, which can then be absorbed.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Different enzymes digest different food substances.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In ruminants, which have herbivorous diets, microorganisms in the gut produce another enzyme, cellulase, to break down the cellulose cell walls of plant fiber.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Several enzymes can work together in a specific order, creating metabolic pathways.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In a metabolic pathway, one enzyme takes the product of another enzyme as a substrate.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] After the catalytic reaction, the product is then passed on to another enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Sometimes more than one enzyme can catalyze the same reaction in parallel; this can allow more complex regulation: with, for example, a low constant activity provided by one enzyme but an inducible high activity from a second enzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes determine what steps occur in these pathways.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Without enzymes, metabolism would neither progress through the same steps and could not be regulated to serve the needs of the cell.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Most central metabolic pathways are regulated at a few steps, typically through enzymes whose activity involves the phosphorylation by ATP.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Because this reaction releases so much energy, other reactions that are thermodynamically unfavorable can be coupled to ATP hydrolysis, driving the overall series of linked metabolic reactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] There are five main ways that enzyme activity is controlled in the cell.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can be either activated or inhibited by other molecules.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, the end product(s) of a metabolic pathway are often inhibitors for one of the first enzymes of the pathway (usually the first irreversible step, called committed step), thus regulating the amount of end product made by the pathways.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Such a regulatory mechanism is called a negative feedback mechanism, because the amount of the end product produced is regulated by its own concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Negative feedback mechanism can effectively adjust the rate of synthesis of intermediate metabolites according to the demands of the cells.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This helps with effective allocations of materials and energy economy, and it prevents the excess manufacture of end products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Like other homeostatic devices, the control of enzymatic action helps to maintain a stable internal environment in living organisms.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Examples of post-translational modification include phosphorylation, myristoylation and glycosylation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, in the response to insulin, the phosphorylation of multiple enzymes, including glycogen synthase, helps control the synthesis or degradation of glycogen and allows the cell to respond to changes in blood sugar.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Another example of post-translational modification is the cleavage of the polypeptide chain.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Chymotrypsin, a digestive protease, is produced in inactive form as chymotrypsinogen in the pancreas and transported in this form to the stomach where it is activated.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This stops the enzyme from digesting the pancreas or other tissues before it enters the gut.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This type of inactive precursor to an enzyme is known as a zymogen or proenzyme.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme production (transcription and translation of enzyme genes) can be enhanced or diminished by a cell in response to changes in the cell's environment.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This form of gene regulation is called enzyme induction.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, bacteria may become resistant to antibiotics such as penicillin because enzymes called beta-lactamases are induced that hydrolyse the crucial beta-lactam ring within the penicillin molecule.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Another example comes from enzymes in the liver called cytochrome P450 oxidases, which are important in drug metabolism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Induction or inhibition of these enzymes can cause drug interactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzyme levels can also be regulated by changing the rate of enzyme degradation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The opposite of enzyme induction is enzyme repression.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes can be compartmentalized, with different metabolic pathways occurring in different cellular compartments.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, fatty acids are synthesized by one set of enzymes in the cytosol, endoplasmic reticulum and Golgi and used by a different set of enzymes as a source of energy in the mitochondrion, through β-oxidation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In addition, trafficking of the enzyme to different compartments may change the degree of protonation (e.g., the neutral cytoplasm and the acidic lysosome) or oxidative state (e.g., oxidizing periplasm or reducing cytoplasm) which in turn affects enzyme activity.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In contrast to partitioning into membrane bound organelles, enzyme subcellular localisation may also be altered through polymerisation of enzymes into macromolecular cytoplasmic filaments.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In multicellular eukaryotes, cells in different organs and tissues have different patterns of gene expression and therefore have different sets of enzymes (known as isozymes) available for metabolic reactions.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This provides a mechanism for regulating the overall metabolism of the organism.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] For example, hexokinase, the first enzyme in the glycolysis pathway, has a specialized form called glucokinase expressed in the liver and pancreas that has a lower affinity for glucose yet is more sensitive to glucose concentration.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This enzyme is involved in sensing blood sugar and regulating insulin production.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Since the tight control of enzyme activity is essential for homeostasis, any malfunction (mutation, overproduction, underproduction or deletion) of a single critical enzyme can lead to a genetic disease.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] The malfunction of just one type of enzyme out of the thousands of types present in the human body can be fatal.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An example of a fatal genetic disease due to enzyme insufficiency is Tay–Sachs disease, in which patients lack the enzyme hexosaminidase.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] One example of enzyme deficiency is the most common type of phenylketonuria.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Many different single amino acid mutations in the enzyme phenylalanine hydroxylase, which catalyzes the first step in the degradation of phenylalanine, result in build-up of phenylalanine and related products.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Some mutations are in the active site, directly disrupting binding and catalysis, but many are far from the active site and reduce activity by destabilising the protein structure, or affecting correct oligomerisation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This can lead to intellectual disability if the disease is untreated.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Another example is pseudocholinesterase deficiency, in which the body's ability to break down choline ester drugs is impaired.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Oral administration of enzymes can be used to treat some functional enzyme deficiencies, such as pancreatic insufficiency and lactose intolerance.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Another way enzyme malfunctions can cause disease comes from germline mutations in genes coding for DNA repair enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Defects in these enzymes cause cancer because cells are less able to repair mutations in their genomes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This causes a slow accumulation of mutations and results in the development of cancers.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] An example of such a hereditary cancer syndrome is xeroderma pigmentosum, which causes the development of skin cancers in response to even minimal exposure to ultraviolet light.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Similar to any other protein, enzymes change over time through mutations and sequence divergence.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Given their central role in metabolism, enzyme evolution plays a critical role in adaptation.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] A key question is therefore whether and how enzymes can change their enzymatic activities alongside.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] It is generally accepted that many new enzyme activities have evolved through gene duplication and mutation of the duplicate copies although evolution can also happen without duplication.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In addition, MAP is metal-ion dependent while creatinase is not, hence this property was also lost over time.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Small changes of enzymatic activity are extremely common among enzymes.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] In particular, substrate binding specificity (see above) can easily and quickly change with single amino acid changes in their substrate binding pockets.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] This is frequently seen in the main enzyme classes such as kinases.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Artificial (in vitro) evolution is now commonly used to modify enzyme activity or specificity for industrial applications (see below).
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes are used in the chemical industry and other industrial applications when extremely specific catalysts are required.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] Enzymes in general are limited in the number of reactions they have evolved to catalyze and also by their lack of stability in organic solvents and at high temperatures.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] As a consequence, protein engineering is an active area of research and involves attempts to create new enzymes with novel properties, either through rational design or *in vitro* evolution.
[src:bradytroph/enzyme] These efforts have begun to be successful, and a few enzymes have now been designed "from scratch" to catalyze reactions that do not occur in nature.
